{"id":14881924,"mediaExerciseId":"0216fbd0-cf9e-4940-b8b0-ccbdc494d608","exerciseName":"6","chapterName":"25","chapterTitle":"Option Valuation","groupId":612508,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":856,"solutions":[{"id":6515701,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this exercise,  we are going to learn about put-call parity. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"To start with, let's define put-call parity. \n\nA **put-call parity** is the correlation between a call and put option which is connected on the same underlying futures contract. This option contract has the same exercise price, expiration date, and asset. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The equation of put call parity is illustrated below: \n\n$$\\text{S}+\\text{P}=\\text{X}(\\text{E})^{\\text{rt}}+\\text{C}$$\n\nWhere: \n\n- S - Current price of the stock\n- PV - Present value of strike price\n- P - Put option\n- C - Call option\n- r - Risk-free rate\n- t - Time\n\nThe sum of the stock price and put option is equal to the sum of the present value of the strike price and call option. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Here are the parameters to solve the requirement : \n\n|Given | | \n|--|--| \n|Call option (C)|$8.64 | \n|Put option (P) | $5.99 |\n|Exercise price of call option |$50 | \n|e | 2.71828| \n|Time (t) |4 months; 4/12; 0.3333 | \n|Stock Price (S) |$52.27 | \n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Now, using the equation in Step 3, the risk free rate is solved below: \n\n&nbsp;\n\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\$52.27+\\$5.99&=[(\\$50)(2.71828)^{-(\\textbf{r})(0.3333)}]+\\$8.64\\\\[10pt]\n\\$58.26&=[(\\$50)(2.71828)^{-(\\textbf{r})(0.3333)}]+\\$8.64\\\\[10pt]\n\\$58.26-\\$8.64&=[(\\$50)(2.71828)^{-(\\textbf{r})(0.3333)}]\\\\[10pt]\n\\frac{\\$49.62}{\\$50}&=2.71828^{-(\\textbf{r})(0.3333)}\\\\[20pt]\n\\$0.9924&=2.71828^{-(\\textbf{r})(0.3333)}\\\\[20pt]\n\\textbf{r}&=\\boxed{0.0229\\space\\text{or}\\space 2.29\\%}\n\\end{aligned}$$\n\nTherefore, the risk free interest rate is 2.29%. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"d27bf3c6-6778-4816-ac28-8020f2251d11","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881925,"exerciseName":"7","page":856,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"4cd24e78-a07f-4309-86df-284513af5586","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-25-questions-and-problems-7-4cd24e78-a07f-4309-86df-284513af5586"},{"id":14881926,"exerciseName":"8","page":856,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"3d86a7a4-fe55-4646-9d30-b422086ec3ed","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-97